The fixture is a single file with no design system around it, so the refactor has to both fix `Card.tsx` *and* introduce the minimum scaffolding it leans on (a `tokens` module). Here's the proposal.

## Refactor plan

**1. Extract design tokens** â†’ fixes `design_token_escape` (crime_00002)

Create `src/tokens.ts` so the literal colors/radii live in one place and agents extending the file can't silently copy a hex forward:

```ts
// src/tokens.ts
export const color = {
  surface: "var(--color-surface)",         // was #ff00aa  (clearly a placeholder)
  textPrimary: "var(--color-text-primary)",// was #0a0a0a
  textSecondary: "var(--color-text-2)",    // was #333333
  textMuted: "var(--color-text-muted)",    // was #666666
  border: "var(--color-border)",           // was #cccccc
  focusRing: "var(--color-focus-ring)",    // was #1a73e8
  shadow: "var(--color-shadow)",           // was rgb(0,0,0)
} as const;

export const space = { md: "var(--space-md)" } as const;      // was 24px
export const radius = { md: "var(--radius-md)" } as const;
export const shadow = { sm: "var(--shadow-sm)" } as const;    // replaces hand-rolled "0 2px 4px"
```

The 9 raw values flagged in evidence (`#ff00aa`, `#0a0a0a`, `#cccccc`, `#1a73e8`, `rgb(0,0,0)`, `#333333`, `#666666`, plus the `boxShadow` literal) all collapse into token references. The CSS-var indirection means the next agent edits a token, not a component.

**2. Use a real button + ARIA fallback** â†’ fixes `accessible_interaction_risk` (crime_00001)

The outer `<div onClick>` is the interactive element. Two routes; pick (a):

- **(a) Preferred:** make the wrapper a `<button type="button">`. That gets keyboard focus, Enter/Space activation, and screen-reader semantics for free. Reset the user-agent button styles (`appearance: none`, `text-align: inherit`, transparent background) since the visual is card-shaped, not button-shaped.
- **(b) If the card must remain a `<div>`** (e.g. it contains other interactive children, which would be invalid nested inside a button): keep the `<div>` but add `role="button"`, `tabIndex={0}`, `aria-label="Open card"` (or similar), and an `onKeyDown` handler that triggers on `Enter`/`Space`.

The current Card has no nested interactives, so (a) is the right call.

**3. Fluid sizing + breakpoint** â†’ fixes `responsive_fragility` (crime_00003)

The three offenders flagged were `width: 800px`, `width: 720px`, `fontSize: 18px`, with no `@media` in the file.

- Outer card: `width: 100%; max-width: 50rem` (â‰ˆ the old 800px ceiling) instead of a hard `width: 800`. `height: 600` becomes `min-height` or is dropped â€” card height should flow from content.
- Inner content column: drop `width: 720`. Use a CSS grid (`grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr) 15rem`) so the sidebar gets a fixed-ish track and the body fills the rest, with a `@media (max-width: 40rem)` rule collapsing it to a single column.
- Typography: `fontSize: clamp(1rem, 0.9rem + 0.3vw, 1.125rem)` instead of a raw `18px`. `14px` sidebar text becomes `0.875rem`.

This is easier with a CSS module than inline `style={}` (you can't write `@media` inline), so move the styles out:

## Refactored `Card.tsx`

```tsx
import { color, space, radius, shadow } from "./tokens";
import styles from "./Card.module.css";

export function Card({
  children,
  onActivate,
  label = "Open card",
}: {
  children: React.ReactNode;
  onActivate?: () => void;
  label?: string;
}) {
  return (
    <button
      type="button"
      className={styles.card}
      onClick={onActivate}
      aria-label={label}
    >
      <div className={styles.body}>{children}</div>
      <aside className={styles.sidebar}>sidebar</aside>
    </button>
  );
}
```

```css
/* src/Card.module.css */
.card {
  all: unset;                /* drop UA button chrome â€” accessibility (1) */
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 1fr) 15rem;
  gap: var(--space-md);
  width: 100%;               /* responsive (3) */
  max-width: 50rem;
  padding: var(--space-md);
  background: var(--color-surface);     /* tokens (2) */
  color: var(--color-text-primary);
  border: 1px solid var(--color-border);
  border-radius: var(--radius-md);
  box-shadow: var(--shadow-sm);
  cursor: pointer;
}
.card:focus-visible { outline: 2px solid var(--color-focus-ring); }

.body { font-size: clamp(1rem, 0.9rem + 0.3vw, 1.125rem); }   /* responsive (3) */
.sidebar { font-size: 0.875rem; color: var(--color-text-muted); }

@media (max-width: 40rem) {                                   /* responsive (3) */
  .card { grid-template-columns: 1fr; }
  .sidebar { font-size: 0.8125rem; }
}
```

## Mapping back to the findings

| Finding | Change |
|---|---|
| `design_token_escape` (crime_00002) | 9 inline hex/rgb/shadow literals â†’ `tokens.ts` + CSS variables; `boxShadow` and `outlineColor` become `var(--shadow-sm)` / `var(--color-focus-ring)`. |
| `accessible_interaction_risk` (crime_00001) | `<div onClick>` â†’ `<button type="button">` with `aria-label`; native keyboard focus + Enter/Space activation; `:focus-visible` ring for visible focus. |
| `responsive_fragility` (crime_00003) | `width: 800` â†’ `width: 100%; max-width: 50rem`; inner fixed `width: 720` removed in favor of a CSS grid; `fontSize: 18` â†’ `clamp(...)`; mobile `@media` collapses the two-column grid. |

## Notes / things to watch

- If consumers rely on the old onClick-on-div pattern, `onActivate` needs to be wired at call sites â€” that's a small breaking change worth flagging in the PR.
- `all: unset` on the button drops *all* UA styling. Test focus, hover, disabled, and HCM (Windows High Contrast) before merging â€” that's the usual regret with this pattern.
- If the card ever needs to contain a nested interactive (a link, another button), switch to fallback (b) â€” nesting interactives inside a `<button>` is invalid HTML.
